'''Charles Stewart Sharp''' {{ post-nominals | country = HKG | JP }} was a British businessman in Hong Kong active in the early 1900s.

He worked with the [[Gibb, Livingston & Co.]], one of the leading mercantile firms in the colony and subsequently was elected as chairman of the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] in 1902. During his spell as chairman of the Chamber of Commerce, he held a committee meeting on the question of [[Hong Kong dollar|local currency]] on the [[gold standard]] and concluded that Hong Kong should stay in the course of [[silver standard|silver basis]] as the colony's largest trading partner, China, remained on silver standard. China and Hong Kong did not abandon silver standard until 1935.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Local Currency|newspaper=The Hong Kong Telegraph|date=18 February 1902|page=4}}</ref>

He was made [[Justice of the Peace]] in 1891.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hong Kong Government Gazette|work=Hong Kong Government|date=2 May 1891}}</ref> and was member of the Medical Board since 1901.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hong Kong Government Gazette|work=Hong Kong Government|date=13 June 1902}}</ref> He was part of the Committee of Inquiry into the Adequacy of the Staff of the Medical Department and the committee's report in 1901 recommended a scale of reform in the Medical Department.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Committee of Inquiry into the Adequacy of the Staff of the Medical Department|work=Hong Kong Government|date=1901}}</ref> 

He was appointed [[unofficial member]] of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] for a six-year-term from 23 April 1902<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hong Kong Government Gazette|work=Hong Kong Government|date=2 May 1902}}</ref> but resigned in 1904.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hong Kong Government Gazette|work=Hong Kong Government|date=16 September 1904}}</ref> He notably helped amending the Public Health and Buildings Ordinance of 1903 during his time as the member of the legislature. He was also appointed as unofficial member of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] on 12 June 1902 during the absence of [[Thomas Henderson Whitehead|T. H. Whitehead]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hong Kong Government Gazette|work=Hong Kong Government|date=13 June 1902}}</ref>

